ce:section.ce:para:
The morphological structures of NiCo-MOF, NiCo-MOF@CAn and NiCo-MOF@CAn materials were observed by field emission scanning electron microscopy (SEM). As shown in Fig. 2
                     , the three materials showed some difference in the morphology. NiCo-MOF (Fig. 2a) consisted of many irregular stacks of continuous nanosheets, which connected together and formed micropores. After introducing CQD-CA and CQD-Can for preparing NiCo-MOF composite, the morphology of the material changed significantly (Fig. 2b–c). The microporous structure of the material was found to be more pronounced and the nanosheets showed a more regular arrangement compared to NiCo-MOF, indicating that hybridizing CQDs could modulate NiCo-MOF's morphology to some extent. Transmission electron microscope (TEM) images (Fig. 3
                     ) showed the flake structure of NiCo-MOF@Can. The small black dots on the flake in Fig. 3a were CQDs. Their size was relatively uniform. The diameter was about 4 nm. According to Fig. 3b, the lattice spacing of the CQDs was about 0.21 nm, which agreed very well with the (100)-crystalline planar spacing of CQDs [16], implying that the CQDs might be successfully introduced into NiCo-MOF.
